Discovery says there is no near-term impact on its current primary health care clients following a ruling which revoked the insurer’s permission to sell cheap primary health care products. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Discovery says there is no near-term impact on its current primary health care clients following a ruling which revoked the insurer’s permission to sell cheap primary health care products.
Cheaper primary health insurance plans, which offer less cover than traditional medical scheme packages, require an exemption from the Medical Schemes Act. READ: Discovery accused of racism In its ruling, the Council for Medical Schemes appeal board said Discovery Life had failed to build a convincing argument for an 'exceptional case' that would warrant exemption from the act. Discovery is not allowed to enrol any new members in these products. The latest development may disrupt the insurer’s plans to expand this part of its business. * For more, watch the interview above.